args:
When Nevin finds Alfie and asks why he fled,
the boy reveals that his mother, Elise, holds the
key to perdition. Elsewhere, Elise reveals the
same secret to Mordecai and Ilia before leaving
to obtain a Scroll in exchange for their help.
Are you TRYING to get attacked by fiends?!\nWhat were you thinking?!
Lemme go! You people are the bad guys!
Might you elaborate on that notion?
You're after the key to perdition!
Ah, so you overheard us. But how is it\nthat you know of the key?
Unless... Are you its keeper?! Is that the\nreason you refused to speak?!
I don't think that's it, Ramiel.
Alfie isn't the keyholder. It's one of his\nparents—his ADOPTIVE parents.
Which is why he took off into the\nmountains at night to try and warn them.
Your being the son of a keyholder\nwould explain why you're so hung up\non the subject of blood relations.
Ah, of course. A key to perdition can\nonly be passed to a blood heir.
I'm not telling you where she is!\nDo what you want—I'll never talk!
I already can't do anything to help her,\nso the least I can do is not make her life\neven worse.
What do you mean by that?
I always thought that once I took the key,\nmom would finally be free.
But now I know I'm adopted,\nwhich means I can't free her.
I love her so much, but I can't do anything\nto help her! I'm just... I'm USELESS!
It seems the Northern Church is looking\nfor the same thing we are in this city.
At this rate, they might even beat us\nto the Scrolls of Perdition.
Do you have any brilliant ideas?
Fresh out at the moment, actually.
...Huh? Oh, hey, Elise. Hope we didn't\nwake you there.
Whaaaat?! Nooooo! I'm ALIA.\nYep! Just boring, plain-old—
No! You are the girl who cast herself into\nthe otherworld a thousand years ago\nto save the world from calamity!
You are the first daughter of the Goddess,\nraised by Her own hand.
Wait, but how do you...? Oh, crap!\nYOU'RE the keyholder!
Yes, I possess a bloodline the Goddess\ncharged with holding a key to perdition.
Well, this is a fine piece of news!
Actually, can we take a moment to sort\nthis out? I'm still sorta reeling here.
So you live here in Stellatea?
Not in the city, no. I have a small dwelling\nin the mountains, concealed by a barrier.
That must be some barrier indeed! I did\nnot think it possible for people to survive\nin such harsh conditions.
I was told that my ancestor was a great\nsorcerer in the Goddess's service.
Perhaps my family's innate skill with\nmagic is rooted in our bloodline.
We have a deep proficiency with potent\nbarrier spells which has kept the key safe\nthroughout the generations.
We leave our shelter only in the rarest of\ntimes, preferring instead a modest life of\nself-sufficiency within its confines.
But here you are in the city at the\nbusiest time of year. That's risky.
Are you really looking for your son?

I am. This is the one time of the year he's
allowed to go into the city; the boy needs
SOME experience of the outside world,
after all.
But when he didn't come home,\nyou left the barrier to find him.
Yes, and I fear he is in terrible danger,\nseeing as others are already looking\nfor me in this place.
Yeah, we need to find him, and fast.
Shameless as this is, Lady Ilia,\nI must ask a favor of you.
I will make for a cavern in the woods,\naccess the otherworld with my key,\nand retrieve my Scroll of Perdition.
I am. The volume I guard is something\nyou must read.
In return, I ask only that you find my son\nand keep him safe. I know this is a bold\nrequest, but please, I beg it of you!
That sounds like what we were going to\ndo anyway. Doesn't it, Ilia?
Yeah, we'd help even if you didn't give us\na damn thing. Don't worry about it.
Still, I would entrust the Scroll to you.\nI will depart for the woods at once.
It's dangerous out there at night.\nBetter let us come with you.
